<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-669-655  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 669 655.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Nov 26 1990 v219 n23 pS8(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Telcos park fiber at the curb: fiber to the curb will help speedfiber into the loop. And bringing it home requires just a shorttrip up the driveway. (Transmission Special: Fiber Explodes intothe Local Loop)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Karpinski, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Attempts to bring fiber to the home are stalled at the curb, butthis is not seen as a defeat.andP;  As trials of fiber-to-the-home(FTTH) in 1989 gave way to trials of fiber-to-the-curb (FTTC) in1990, telephone companies realized that there is value in sharedresources.andP;  Bringing fiber directly to the home is expensivebecause dedicated fibers and optoelectronic components quicklydrive up costs.andP;  The answer is to carry fiber to the curbside,whence short non-fiber drops can carry most, if not all, of thehigh-bandwidth services that are now available.andP;  Volumedeployments, it is thought, will decrease costs further.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsTelephone systemsTelephone companiesBell Regional Holding Companies.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Fiber trials. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>